<HEAD>Rushdie Says He Wants Reconciliation With Islam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <PERSON>Salman Rushdie</PERSON> says he is optimistic that he can
work out a reconciliation with Moslems, but an Iranian leader says
the death sentence against the Indian-born author of ``The Satanic
Verses'' can never be lifted.
   ``I have to hope that the atmosphere is gradually changing. I
think there's various signs that it might be,'' <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION>CBS
News</ORGANIZATION> correspondent <PERSON>Mike Wallace</PERSON> in an interview for <DATE>Sunday</DATE>'s
edition of ``60 Minutes.''
   In a separate interview, Rajei-Khorrasani, a powerful leader in
<LOCATION>Iran</LOCATION>'s parliament, said the death sentence cannot be lifted
``because it is a religious fact, which remains there forever.''
   Rushdie, 43, a Bombay-born British subject, has been in hiding
under police guard since <DATE>Feb. 14, 1989</DATE>, when <LOCATION>Iran</LOCATION>'s spiritual
leader, <PERSON>Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini</PERSON>, declared his novel an affront
to Islam and ordered Moslems to kill him. Khomeini died <DATE>June 3,
1989</DATE>.
   Iranian clerics offered a <MONEY>$5.2-million</MONEY> bounty for <ORGANIZATION>Rushdie</ORGANIZATION>'s
assassination.
   Among parts of the ``The Satanic Verses'' many Moslems find
offensive are a scene in which prostitutes are given the names of
the prophet <PERSON>Mohammed</PERSON>'s wives, and implications that <PERSON>Mohammed</PERSON> wrote
the <LOCATION>Koran</LOCATION>, the Moslem holy book.
   <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON> said he never meant to insult the Moslem world.
   ``If I'm accused of calling the prophet's wives whores, I didn't
do it,'' he said.
   ``I'm not this kind of creature with horns and a tail that's
been painted,'' he said. ``There is actually very little in
`Satanic Verses' that hasn't been, in fact, quite commonplace
discussion in the Moslem world for hundreds of years.''
   <PERSON>Wallace</PERSON> said he met with the author at a police officers' club
on the outskirts of <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
