<DESCRIPT>  EDITORIAL; BOOK; WRITING; PROFESSIONAL  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  IS Salman Rushdie a born-again Muslim, seeking, as he wrote in the Dec. 28 New
York Times op-ed page, to "enter into the body of Islam after a lifetime spent
outside it"?;    Or is he tired of nearly two years of hiding from fanatics
who pledged to carry out the Ayatollah Khomeini's death sentence on the
heretical author of "The Satanic Verses"?  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Editorial  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SALMAN'S SEA OF STORIES
DESPITE HIS CONVERSION, RUSHDIE'S RIGHT TO
WRITE REMAINS UNDER ATTACK  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Editorials  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Anyone who's read one of <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON>'s multi-layered, allegorical, fantastical,
satirical novels would suspect that nothing <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON> says has only one
meaning.;    After a <ORGANIZATION>Christmas Eve</ORGANIZATION> meeting with six moderate Muslim leaders,
<PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON> issued a statement saying "I do not agree with any statements in my
novel . . . uttered by any of the characters who insult the prophet Mohammed,
or cast aspersions upon Islam, or upon the authenticity of the holy <LOCATION>Koran</LOCATION>, or
who reject the divinity of Allah.";    About 1.2-million English-language
copies of "The Satanic Verses," about the improbable adventures of a Muslim
immigrant in <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>, have been sold (though not necessarily read), and the
book has been translated into 15 languages.;    <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON> described the book in
his op-ed piece as "a parable of how a man can be destroyed by loss of faith .
. . the dreams in which all the so-called 'insults' (to Islam) occur are
portraits of his disintegration and explicitly referred to in the novel as
punishments and retributions.";    While not withdrawing the book from stores,
<PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON> promised not to permit new translations of "The Satanic Verses," or an
English-language paperback edition, and pledged "to work for a better
understanding of Islam.";    <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON> may be able to sit and schmooze with
leaders of the Islamic Society for the <ORGANIZATION>Promotion of Religious Tolerance</ORGANIZATION> in the
<LOCATION>United Kingdom</LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION>Supreme Council of Scholars of Islamic Affairs</ORGANIZATION>, but
he's still having trouble with the ayatollah's heirs.;    An editorial in the
newspaper Tehran Abrar promptly rejected his apology, saying the ayatollah's
death sentence "is irrevocable even if (Rushdie) repents.";    On the other
hand, <LOCATION>Iran</LOCATION>'s new leaders are prone to playing good mullah, bad mullah, and
some believe <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON>'s recantation eventually will do the trick.;    The
religious thugs' attempt to silence <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON> is an affront to human freedom. It
is distinctly unpleasant to see a novelist forced to beg forgiveness and
suppress wider publication of his own book.;    Still, the writer is not only
alive, he's writing.;    In <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON>'s new book, "Haroun and the Sea of
Stories," which is dedicated to his son, the boy <PERSON>Haroun</PERSON> undertakes a quest to
free his father, the <ORGANIZATION>Shah of Blah</ORGANIZATION>, from storytellers' block caused by the
fanatical Khattam-Shud, who has poisoned the Ocean of the Streams of Story. As
the enemy of "stories and fancies and dreams" explains to Haroun: "Your world,
my world, all worlds are there to be Ruled. And inside every single story,
inside every Stream in the <LOCATION>Ocean</LOCATION>, there lies a world, a storyworld, that I
cannot Rule at all. And that is the reason why.";    And that is the reason
why <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON> must not be silenced.  </TEXT>
