<HEAD>Iran Calls On Moslem Nations To Stand United Against Rushdie</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with speech by Iranian official,
reaction from chairman of Islamic Conference. Edits to tighten. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALY MAHMOUD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran called on Moslem officials
attending a conference here <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> to support <LOCATION>Iran</LOCATION>'s decision to
break relations with <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> and call for the execution of author
<PERSON>Salman Rushdie</PERSON>.
   But the <LOCATION>Saudi Arabian</LOCATION> foreign minister, who is chairman of the
46-member <ORGANIZATION>Organization of Islamic Conference</ORGANIZATION>, said he believed the
organization would only denounce <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON> and his book, ``The Satanic
Verses.''
   ``<LOCATION>Iran</LOCATION> was honored to have broken ties with the leader of the
plot,'' <PERSON>Mohammad Taskhiri</PERSON>, head of <LOCATION>Iran</LOCATION>'s delegation, said referring
to <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> in a speech at the foreign ministers' conference.
   Taskhiri urged all Islamic governments to stand united against
what he described as ``these mean attempts to offend the image of
the <PERSON>Prophet Mohammed</PERSON>, his wives and daughters.''
   ``If we are silent now, the West will make a film and then a
video'' of ``The Satanic Verses,'' he said.
   ``We demand that the punishment decreed by Allah be meted out on
that apostate (Rushdie). We also demand that all Islamic countries
boycott <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> culturally and, if that doesn't work, then
politically and economically.''
   The punishment <PERSON>Taskhiri</PERSON> referred to was a fatwa, or religious
ruling, issued by the Iranian leader, <PERSON>Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini</PERSON>,
ordering <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON>'s execution for blasphemy.
   Iranian clerics later offered up to <MONEY>$5.2 million</MONEY> to anyone who
killed the 41-year-old author, who was born into a Moslem family in
<LOCATION>India</LOCATION>, but who later moved to <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>, where he has been under
police guard since the death threat.
   The Saudi Arabian foreign minister, <PERSON>Prince Saud al-Faisal</PERSON>, told
reporters:
   ``The conference examined the insufferable affronts and
distortions of Islam in <LOCATION>Rushdie</LOCATION>'s book, which has been strongly
condemned and denounced.''
   He indicated the conference could not condone <LOCATION>Iran</LOCATION>'s order to
kill <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON> and punish <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> for protecting him.
   He said the conference attaches great importance to the ``spirit
of harmony between all world civilizations and countries.''
   In <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON>'s novel, the archangel <PERSON>Gabriel</PERSON> is depicted as an
Indian movie star. A scribe claims he altered the words of the holy
Koran _ considered the word of God _ without the prophet noticing.
And a whorehouse triples its business when its 12 women take on the
identities of the prophets' wives.
   At least 19 people have been killed in anti-Rushdie protests in
<LOCATION>Pakistan</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>, and the book has been banned in those countries
and others, including <LOCATION>Egypt</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Bangladesh</LOCATION>.
   In <LOCATION>Peshawar</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Pakistan</LOCATION>, on <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, a bomb exploded and tore a
two-foot hole in the roof of a <ORGANIZATION>British Council</ORGANIZATION> library. A library
official linked the blast, in which no one was hurt, to Moslem
outrage over <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON>'s novel.
   <LOCATION>Sudan</LOCATION> announced <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> it was banning all books written by
<PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON> or issued by his publisher, <PERSON>Viking Penguin</PERSON>.
   In an interview earlier <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, <PERSON>Taskhiri</PERSON> insisted that <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON>
be judged according to the sharia, or Koranic law _ which he said
requires the death sentence for blasphemy. ``That would be the end
of our request,'' <PERSON>Taskhiri</PERSON> said. ``It is impossible for <LOCATION>Iran</LOCATION> to
change its basic position on the issue.''
   Conference sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said most
delegates follow another interpretation of the sharia, insisting
that anyone accused of blasphemy be given a fair trial and an
oppportunity to repent.
   Islamic theologians meeting in <LOCATION>Mecca</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Saudi Arabia</LOCATION>, the holiest
shrine of Islam, issued a declaration <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> supporting that
interpretation.
   Several delegates were trying to work out a compromise between
<LOCATION>Iran</LOCATION> and the more liberal group led by <LOCATION>Saudi Arabia</LOCATION>, the sources
said.
</TEXT>
