<HEAD>Iran Rips Middle East Trip By Charles And Diana</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABU DHABI, United Arab Emirates (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran says the current
<LOCATION>Middle East</LOCATION> tour of Prince <PERSON>Charles</PERSON> and <PERSON>Princess Diana</PERSON> is a hostile
affront to Moslems who want <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> to ban <PERSON>Salman Rushdie</PERSON>'s novel
``The Satanic Verses.''
   Tehran Radio on <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> accused the British government of
trying to exploit the trip and ``give a cold shoulder'' to the
world's Moslems. But it warned that <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> could not avoid facing
``their wrath.''
   On the second day of their official visit to the <ORGANIZATION>United Arab
Emirates</ORGANIZATION> <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, the heir to the British throne and his wife were
steeped in Arab traditions. There was camel racing, sword dancing
and open-air lamb roasting.
   The couple is on an official one-week tour of <LOCATION>Kuwait</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Bahrain</LOCATION> and
the Emirates that was announced last <DATE>June</DATE>. Charles will then fly
alone to <LOCATION>Saudi Arabia</LOCATION> for a private visit.
   <ORGANIZATION>Tehran Radio</ORGANIZATION>, monitored in <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>, noted that the visit was
taking place while the 45-nation <ORGANIZATION>Organization of Islamic Conference</ORGANIZATION>
was meeting in the <LOCATION>Saudi</LOCATION> capital, <LOCATION>Riyadh</LOCATION>, with ``The Satanic
Verses'' at the top of the agenda.
   <LOCATION>Iran</LOCATION> on <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> told conference delegates it was honored to
have broken relations with <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> over the <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON> affair. It
reiterated its call for the execution of Indian-born British author
first issued <DATE>Feb. 14</DATE> by fundamentalist patriarch <PERSON>Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini</PERSON>.
   ``Now under such circumstances when the British government has
applied all its resources for inflicting a blow upon Islam and
insulting our prophet, how can the presence of the British crown
prince in Islamic states be justified?'' said a commentary by <ORGANIZATION>Tehran
Radio</ORGANIZATION>.
   Many Moslems say ``The Satanic Verses'' blasphemes Islam by
suggesting the <LOCATION>Koran</LOCATION>, Islam's holy book, was invented by the prophet
Mohammed rather than received directly from God, and for giving
prostitutes the names of <ORGANIZATION>Mohammed</ORGANIZATION>'s wives.
  
</TEXT>
