<HEAD>Khomeini Thanks Moslems For Support</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Moslems, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <PERSON>Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini</PERSON> expressed his
thanks <DATE>Monday</DATE> to Moslems who supported his order that <PERSON>Salman Rushdie</PERSON>
be killed for writing ``The Satanic Verses.''
   Iranian television quoted a statement from the 88-year-old
patriarch's office as saying it ``was inundated by waves of
telegrams and letters, and pledges of support and readiness to carry
out the Imam's order, most of them from Islamic scholars and leaders
who organized glorious rallies and protests, all of which were
reported to the Imam.''
   ``The Imam expressed his thanks to all the people for their pure
feelings, which tell of hearts full of faith,'' the statement said.
   Khomeini's thanks coincided with the opening of a four-day
conference in <LOCATION>Riyadh</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Saudi Arabia</LOCATION>, of member nations of the
<ORGANIZATION>Organization of Islamic Conference</ORGANIZATION>. Iran wants the meeting to take
action about <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON> and ``The Islamic Verses,'' which Moslems
believe blasphemes Islam.
   According to the television, 190 members of <LOCATION>Iran</LOCATION>'s parliament
sent a letter to the <LOCATION>Riyadh</LOCATION> conference demanding discussion of the
book and Western support for <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON>.
   Arab diplomatic sources said <PERSON>Khomeini</PERSON>'s death threat had not
found support at the conference.
   He issued the order <DATE>Feb. 14</DATE>, directing his followers to hunt down
and kill <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON>, and Iranian clerics offered a reward of <MONEY>$5.2
million</MONEY>.
   Rushdie went into hiding. He was born in <LOCATION>Bombay</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>, to Moslem
parents but now is a British citizen and has said he does not
practice religion.
   Moslems say his novel blashphemes Islam in a scene in which
prostitutes are given the names of Mohammed's wives and in its
suggestion that the prophet wrote the holy Koran rather than
receiving it from <LOCATION>Allah</LOCATION>.
   Iran broke diplomatic relations with <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> <DATE>last week</DATE> because
Prime Minister <PERSON>Margaret Thatcher</PERSON>'s government would not suppress the
book.
   Tehran's official <ORGANIZATION>Islamic Republic News Agency</ORGANIZATION> said <DATE>Monday</DATE> people
in the African nations of <LOCATION>Niger</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Zimbabwe</LOCATION> support <PERSON>Khomeini</PERSON>'s
action. It said Premier <PERSON>Mamane Oumarou</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Niger</LOCATION> endorsed the
execution order and a Moslem youth group in <LOCATION>Zimbabwe</LOCATION> had vowed to
bring <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON> ``to divine justice.''
   The news agency said two <LOCATION>Tehran</LOCATION> newspapers called for an economic
boycott of <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> and a third recommended breaking relations with
<LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION>.
   According to the latest available figures, <LOCATION>Iran</LOCATION> imported goods
worth <MONEY>$528 million</MONEY> from <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> in <DATE>1987</DATE> and sold it exports valued
at <MONEY>$321</MONEY>.
   <LOCATION>Israel</LOCATION>'s largest book fair opened <DATE>Monday</DATE> in <LOCATION>Jerusalem</LOCATION>, with
100,000 books from 42 countries on display, and ``The Satanic
Verses'' was the main attraction.
   State radio said branches of the <ORGANIZATION>British Council</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Israel</LOCATION>
removed the <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON> book from their lending library shelves, but it
quoted council officials as saying it remained available on request.
   Prime Minister <PERSON>Brian Mulroney</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION>, whose government briefly
halted imports of the novel, was in <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> on <DATE>Monday</DATE> and said: ``I
expressed to <PERSON>Mrs. Thatcher</PERSON> the view of my government that ... it is
unacceptable for anyone to place a price on the head of a private
citizen for any reason at all, least of all for the expression of a
literary view.''
   President <PERSON>Richard von Weizsaecker</PERSON> of <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION> said <DATE>Monday</DATE>
that religious tolerance should be the starting point of a <LOCATION>Middle
East</LOCATION> peace settlement.
   At a dinner for visiting President <PERSON>Hosni Mubarak</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Egypt</LOCATION>, he
acknowledged that <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON>'s book had offended Moslems, but said hurt
feelings were not grounds for violation of national sovereignty and
legal rights.
   <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION> is <LOCATION>Iran</LOCATION>'s biggest trading partner. Iran imported
<MONEY>$1.3 billion</MONEY> worth of goods from it in <DATE>1987</DATE> and sold <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION>
exports worth <MONEY>$560 million</MONEY>.
   <LOCATION>Bonn</LOCATION> has joined the 12-nation <ORGANIZATION>European Community</ORGANIZATION> in recalling its
envoy from <LOCATION>Iran</LOCATION> to protest the death sentence, canceled plans for a
Cabinet minister to visit <LOCATION>Tehran</LOCATION> and suspended more than <MONEY>$1 billion</MONEY>
in credits for <LOCATION>Iran</LOCATION>.
   Two prominent members of the Swedish Academy, which awards the
Nobel prizes, announced in <LOCATION>Stockholm</LOCATION> they would boycott the academy
to protest its failure to speak out as a body on <ORGANIZATION>Rushdie</ORGANIZATION>'s behalf.
   Author <PERSON>Kerstin Ekman</PERSON>, one of two women in the 18-member academy,
told Swedish television she was dropping ``all work in the academy,
which means in effect I am leaving it.''
   <PERSON>Lars Gyllensten</PERSON>, a former permanent secretary of the academy,
said he would boycott its regular <DATE>Thursday</DATE> meetings but remain on
the administrative committee and Nobel institution.
   Rules of the 200-year-old organization say members are elected
for life and vacate their seats only at death or if they commit a
serious crime.
</TEXT>
