<HEAD>Moslems Don't See Need To Disrupt `Satanic Verses' Reading</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>IOWA CITY, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arab students who helped sponsor a public
reading of ``The Satanic Verses'' say they may not like author
<PERSON>Salman Rushdie</PERSON>, but they want to show that not all Moslems support
<PERSON>Ayatollah Khomeini</PERSON>'s death decree against him.
   About 300 people attended <DATE>Friday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME>'s reading and panel
discussion on the <ORGANIZATION>University of Iowa</ORGANIZATION> campus. Twenty-five people read
two-minute selections from the book that many Moslems claim
blasphemes their faith.
   Wan <PERSON>Hasni</PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION>Iowa City Islamic Society</ORGANIZATION> and a
statistics student, said he and other Muslims attended the session
at the <ORGANIZATION>Iowa Memorial Union</ORGANIZATION> ``to hear the views, the feelings of
others in the American community have about this book.''
   ``A demonstration is appropriate if we need one. But it would
have served no purpose to disrupt the reading,'' he said.
   <PERSON>Saadi Simawe</PERSON>, a representative of the <ORGANIZATION>Arab Students Association</ORGANIZATION>
who organized the event, said the reading aimed to demonstrate that
not all Moslems support <PERSON>Khomeini</PERSON>'s action.
   ``Fanaticism is always an aspect of insecurity,'' <PERSON>Simawe</PERSON> said.
``I read the <LOCATION>Koran</LOCATION>, I respect the prophet. I think Islam is a great
religion if taken personally. Once you are going to impose it on
others, it is very dangerous.''
   ``The Koran is not fragile, it is not a (blade) of grass that you
can destroy it by a book. It is a living book,'' said <PERSON>Simawe</PERSON>, a
doctoral student from <LOCATION>Iraq</LOCATION> studying English and African-American
World Studies.
   <PERSON>Bill Fuhrmeister</PERSON>, director of security at the university, said a
handful of officers stood guard at the reading in case of
disruptions or violence.
   But the only signs of protest were two Islamic Society members
who quietly held large posters defending <LOCATION>Iran</LOCATION>'s order that Rushdie
be killed.
   ``Freedom of speech does not mean you can insult one-fifth of
earth's population,'' said a sign held by <PERSON>Mubarak Al-Ajmi</PERSON>, also a
student at the <ORGANIZATION>University of Iowa</ORGANIZATION>.
   ``If someone insults your family, you would stand up and do
something about it. Well, what <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON> has insulted is my religion,
which means more to me than even my family,'' <PERSON>Al-Ajmi</PERSON> said.
   <PERSON>Mahmoud Rizig</PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION>Iowa City Islamic Society</ORGANIZATION>, said
he urged his group's members to attend the reading and carry protest
signs but not disrupt the event.
   Rushdie, a British citizen who was born into a Moslem family in
<LOCATION>India</LOCATION>, has been in hiding since <DATE>Feb. 14</DATE>, when Iranian clerics
offered a <MONEY>$5.2 million</MONEY> reward for his death.
   The Writers' Workshop and the International Writing Program at
the university sponsored the reading along with the <ORGANIZATION>Arab Students
Association</ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION>General Union of Palestinian Students</ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION>Indian
Students' Association</ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION>Pakistani Students Association</ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
