<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pro-Iranian captors of three American
educators today threatened to take revenge against <PERSON>Salman Rushdie</PERSON>,
the publishers of his novel ``The Satanic Verses'' and their
supporters for insulting Islam.
   Islamic Jihad for the Liberation of Palestine delivered the
threat in a hand-written statement accompanied by an instant
photograph of American hostages <PERSON>Alann Steen</PERSON>, <PERSON>Robert Polhill</PERSON> and
<PERSON>Jesse Turner</PERSON>.
   The group did not directly threaten the hostages, who appeared in
a photograph released with the document to prove its authenticity.
   The Arabic-language statement, delivered to the office of a
Western news agency in Moslem west <LOCATION>Beirut</LOCATION>, threatened to ``take
revenge against all those who took part in strong and ferocious
campaigns against Islam.''
   In the photograph, shows the three bearded hostages from the
knees up sitting on what appeared to be a bed and looking straight
into the camera.
   Polhill's left arm and hand are noticeably thinner than in a
picture released 14 months earlier, and his left sleeve appears to
have intentionally been hiked up to the elbow to show the arm.
   The document said the revenge would cover ``all institutions and
organizations that insulted in one way or another'' members of
prophet <PERSON>Mohammed</PERSON>'s family, meaning Moslems.
   European governments have recalled their ambassadors from <LOCATION>Iran</LOCATION> to
protest <PERSON>Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini</PERSON>'s decree last week that Moslems
seek out and kill <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON> and his publishers because ``The Satanic
Verses'' blasphemes Islam.
   Authors have led demonstrations of outrage at the threat from
<LOCATION>Iran</LOCATION>'s fundamentalist patriarch, who has refused to accept <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON>'s
apology, and President <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> has called the threat an insult to the
civilized world.
   Rushdie, a naturalized Briton who was born a Moslem in <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>, is
in hiding with his wife in <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> and reportedly under police
guard. Iranian clerics have offered <MONEY>$5.2 million</MONEY> for <ORGANIZATION>Rushdie</ORGANIZATION>'s
murder.
   <PERSON>Steen</PERSON>, <PERSON>Polhill</PERSON> and <PERSON>Turner</PERSON> were kidnapped <DATE>Jan. 24, 1987</DATE>, from the
campus of the American-affiliated <ORGANIZATION>Beirut University College</ORGANIZATION>, where
they held teaching posts. <PERSON>Steen</PERSON>, 49, of <LOCATION>Boston</LOCATION>, taught journalism,
while <PERSON>Polhill</PERSON>, 54, of <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, was assistant professor of business
and <PERSON>Turner</PERSON>, 42, of <LOCATION>Boise</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Idaho</LOCATION>, taught mathematics and computer
science.
   The three are among 15 foreigners missing and believed held
hostage in <LOCATION>Lebanon</LOCATION> by pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem extremists. Nine of
the hostages are American, including <ORGANIZATION>Associated Press</ORGANIZATION> chief <LOCATION>Middle
East</LOCATION> correspondent <PERSON>Terry Anderson</PERSON>, who was kidnapped <DATE>March 16, 1985</DATE>
and is the longest held.
   ``Islamic Jihad for the Liberation of Palestine had persistently
sought to find a peaceful settlement to the hostages' issue, in
accordance with its principles and to show its good intentions in
light of international detente,'' the statement said.
   ``But it seems that imperialism and Zionism consider that Moslems
should go back on their beliefs and principles as if this were the
price of living in the shadow of international detente.''
   The <LOCATION>Beirut</LOCATION> newspaper an-Nahar <DATE>today</DATE> said efforts to free foreign
hostages in <LOCATION>Lebanon</LOCATION> have suffered now that <LOCATION>Iran</LOCATION> and the 12 <ORGANIZATION>European
Economic Community</ORGANIZATION> nations are at loggerheads over <LOCATION>Iran</LOCATION>'s death
threat against <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON>.
   Jihad threatened to strike against American and Israeli interests
for supporting <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON> and his novel and called on ``Moslems all
over the world to stand against the laws of the jungle so that
advocates of these laws would realize that real human values ... lie
in spiritual religions and not in the jungle's system.''
   It described <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON>'s book and the support it has as ``the worst
type of insult against Islam's sacredness.''
   The book was part of ``serious and wide-ranging programs underway
to strike against Islam because it is the force that fights moral
and humanitarian degeneration,'' the statement claimed.
   Many Moslems say <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON>'s book blasphemes Islam by portraying
<ORGANIZATION>Mohammed</ORGANIZATION>'s wives as prostitutes and suggesting he wrote the <LOCATION>Koran</LOCATION>,
the holy book of Islam, rather than receiving it from God.
   In <LOCATION>Beirut</LOCATION>, reactions to <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON>'s ``The Satanic Verses'' have
been slow and conflicting. An advisor to the Sunni Moslem grand
mufti rejected <LOCATION>Iran</LOCATION>'s ruling while the highest Shiite Moslem
religious judge advocated the death sentence.
</TEXT>
