<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Author <PERSON>Salman Rushdie</PERSON>, facing calls for his death
and a multimillion-dollar bounty for the killer, today apologized to
Moslems for the distress caused by the publication of his novel
``The Satanic Verses.''
   However, the official Iranian news agency said the author had
failed to repent or order that his book be withdrawn. A Moslem
leader in <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> welcomed the apology but said the campaign against
the book would continue.
   In a statement issued by his agent, <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON> said: ``I profoundly
regret the distress that publication has occasioned to sincere
followers of Islam.''
   ``Living as we do in a world of many faiths this experience has
served to remind us that we must all be conscious of the
sensibilities of others.''
   The brief statement was also issued to <LOCATION>Iran</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Islamic Republic
News Agency</ORGANIZATION>, and a story was sent to <LOCATION>Iran</LOCATION>, a spokesman for the
agency said.
   Rushdie apologized after his book was banned in six countries and
removed from the shelves of major bookstores in the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>.
   The author's statement came a day after <LOCATION>Iran</LOCATION>'s president, <PERSON>Ali
Khamenei</PERSON>, said the Indian-born Briton could save his life with an
apology.
   Iran's news agency noted the apology but said <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON>'s statement
``made no indication of his repentence or that his slanderous book
would be withdrawn.''
   IRNA, monitored in <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>, said <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON>, who was raised in a
Moslem family, has been ``under growing pressure to make a public
repentence that his statement is seen falling well short of.''
   Two prominent Moslems condemned the Iranian campaign against the
author, which began <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> when Iranian leader <PERSON>Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini</PERSON> said ``The Satanic Verses'' blasphemed Islam and demanded
zealous Moslems kill <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON>. Two Iranian religious leaders later
offered a <MONEY>$5.2 million</MONEY> bounty for Rushdie.
   The Times of <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> today reported that a power struggle may have
prompted <PERSON>Khomeini</PERSON>'s execution order, which sent <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON>, 41, and his
American wife into hiding under the guard of <LOCATION>Scotland</LOCATION> Yard
detectives.
   The <ORGANIZATION>British Foreign Office</ORGANIZATION> said on <DATE>Friday</DATE> that ``considerable
confusion persists'' within the Iranian government and that <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>
``intended to proceed with that fact in mind.'' It did not elaborate.
   Moslems condemned ``The Satanic Verses'' when it was published
late last year to critical acclaim in the <LOCATION>West</LOCATION>.
   Another round of protests began <DATE>Sunday</DATE> with demonstrations in
<LOCATION>Pakistan</LOCATION>, where six people died. The protests spread and another
person was killed and 75 people injured in a series of
demonstrations in <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>.
   After <PERSON>Khomeini</PERSON> also ordered the death of publishers of the novel,
book companies in <LOCATION>France</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Greece</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Turkey</LOCATION> decided
not to publish it. Others in <LOCATION>Finland</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Norway</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Italy</LOCATION> were unswayed.
   Major <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> booksellers such as <PERSON>B. Dalton</PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION>Barnes &amp; Nobel</ORGANIZATION>
removed the novel from their shelves, and <LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION> halted imports. The
book has been officially banned in <LOCATION>Iran</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Pakistan</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Bangladesh</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Egypt</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION>.
   The governments of <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> and the <LOCATION>United
States</LOCATION> condemned the Iranian compaign. The <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> called it
``appalling.''
   The Times of <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> quoted ``a closely involved source'' as
saying <PERSON>Khomeini</PERSON>'s son Ahmad and three hard-line ministers may have
persuaded the 88-year-old spiritual leader to make the death call to
undermine a political rival seeking improved relations with <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>.
   The report said supporters of <LOCATION>Iran</LOCATION>'s parliament speaker, <PERSON>Hashemi
Rafsanjani</PERSON>, believe <PERSON>Khomeini</PERSON>'s son and the government ministers
hoped the death call would deal a blow to British relations and
<PERSON>Rafsanjani</PERSON>.
   Some diplomats in the <LOCATION>Middle East</LOCATION> have speculated the <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON>
issue was promoted by factions in <LOCATION>Iran</LOCATION> opposed to recent moves by
more pragmatic figures, including <PERSON>Rafsanjani</PERSON>, to improve relations
with the <LOCATION>West</LOCATION>.
   But <PERSON>Akhoond Zadeh Basti</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Iran</LOCATION>'s charge d'affaires in <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>, told
<ORGANIZATION>Independent Television News</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Britian</LOCATION> on <DATE>Friday</DATE> that <PERSON>Khomeini</PERSON>'s
call was ``based purely on religious grounds.''
   In <LOCATION>Egypt</LOCATION>, <DATE>1988</DATE> Nobel Prize laureate <PERSON>Naguib Mahfouz</PERSON> <DATE>today</DATE> said
<PERSON>Khomeini</PERSON>'s call ``can undoubtedly be considered terrorism.'' The
76-year-old novelist said in an interview that the ``decision is
against humanity because it is against thought and against human
rights. It is also against Islam because it harms the reputation of
Islam and Moslems in the civilized world.''
   The head of the Shiite Moslem community in <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> on <DATE>Friday</DATE> urged
book companies not to publish the novel, but he denounced <PERSON>Khomeini</PERSON>'s
death call.
   ``The Moslem world is shaken, shocked by this work, which throws
doubt on the authenticity of our holy book, which treats the wives
of the prophet as prostitutes,'' <PERSON>Ayatollah Mehdi Rhouani</PERSON> said from
his <LOCATION>Paris</LOCATION> home in an interview with <ORGANIZATION>The Associated Press</ORGANIZATION>. But he
said <PERSON>Khomeini</PERSON>'s decree was ``contrary to Islamic law, contrary to
international law, contrary to morals.''
   Rushdie's publishers showed the apology to <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Foreign
Office</ORGANIZATION> shortly before it was made public.
   A <ORGANIZATION>Foreign Office</ORGANIZATION> spokesman, who by custom was not identified,
said: ``The statement is, of course, a matter for <PERSON>Mr. Rushdie</PERSON> and
not for the government. But if it serves to calm passions, then that
can only be a good thing.''
   Members of <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s Moslem community welcomed <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON>'s
statement. But leaders of the Islamic community in <LOCATION>Bradford</LOCATION>, where
some copies of the book were burned in public, said their campaign
against it would continue.
   ``I think the apology will calm down the situation but it will
not change the situation overall until the book is withdrawn from
circulation,'' said <PERSON>Liaqat Hussain</PERSON>, general secretary of the
<ORGANIZATION>Bradford Council of Mosques</ORGANIZATION>.
   Viking, the book's publishers in <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> and the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>,
said earlier this week that it and the author ``very much regret the
distress the book has caused.'' But <PERSON>Viking</PERSON> did not apologize for
publishing the book.
   Before today's statement, <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON> had said the novel was
fictional and not blasphemous.
   Moslems say ``The Satanic Verses'' blasphemes their religion by,
among other things, portraying the prophet <PERSON>Mohammed</PERSON>'s wives as
prostitutes and suggesting that he wrote the <LOCATION>Koran</LOCATION>, the holy book of
Islam, rather than receiving it from God.
</TEXT>
