<HEAD>50,000 Marchers Protest Rushdie's Book; Newsweek Banned In Malaysia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 19th graf, `A youth...' to note Rushdie is in hiding.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Saudi-Iran</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HASAN SAEED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 50,000 Moslems left mosques
and marched throughout the capital <DATE>Friday</DATE> before gathering at the
government's headquarters to demand the death of author <PERSON>Salman
Rushdie</PERSON>.
   Also <DATE>Friday</DATE> about 3,000 Moslem fundamentalists in <LOCATION>Sudan</LOCATION>, some
shouting ``Down, down with <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>!'' demanded that <LOCATION>Sudan</LOCATION> break
relations with the British government which has defended publication
of <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON>'s book ``The Satanic Verses.''
   In <LOCATION>Malaysia</LOCATION>, the government banned the <DATE>March 13</DATE> issue of Newsweek
magazine and the <DATE>March 9</DATE> issues of the <ORGANIZATION>Hong Kong-based Far Eastern
Economic Review</ORGANIZATION> for printing extracts from the book.
   Many Moslems find the book blasphemous because it suggests the
prophet <PERSON>Mohammed</PERSON> wrote the Koran instead of receiving it from God
and because its characters include prostitutes who take the names of
<ORGANIZATION>Mohammed</ORGANIZATION>'s wives.
   Several countries including <LOCATION>Bangladesh</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Malaysia</LOCATION> have banned
the book, and <LOCATION>Iran</LOCATION> has offered <MONEY>$5.2 million</MONEY> to any Moslem who kills
<PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON>, an Indian-born Briton of Moslem upbringing.
   Marchers in <LOCATION>Dhaka</LOCATION> chanted ``We will kill Rushdie'' and gathered
near the Secretariat, the headquarters of the government. Several
hundred policemen in riot gear followed the marchers but there was
no violence.
   More than 15,000 followers of Jamaat-e-Islami, a fundamentalist
Moslem party, held another rally in front of the city's main mosque
and religious leaders accused Zionists of ``conspiring against Islam
and its prophet Mohammed.''
   Seven of the country's top religious leaders have called for a
nationwide general strike on <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> to protest the book.
   A youth organization has set up a 15-member death squad to kill
<PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON> if he comes to <LOCATION>Bangladesh</LOCATION>. The group is led by <PERSON>Farooq Ahmed</PERSON>,
who said the squad had no plans to go to <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> to kill <PERSON>Rushdie</PERSON>, who
is in hiding somewhere in <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>.
   The demonstrators in the Sudanese capital, <LOCATION>Khartoum</LOCATION>, urged the
government to break relations with <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> and boycott all its goods.
   The protest, led by the fundamenalist <ORGANIZATION>National Islamic Front</ORGANIZATION>, is
seen as the party's first sign of opposition to Prime Minister <PERSON>Sadek
Mahdi</PERSON>.
   Mahdi is in the process of forming a new broad-based government
that would start talks with <LOCATION>Sudan</LOCATION>'s southern rebels to end the
6-year-old civil war.
   The <ORGANIZATION>National Islamic Front</ORGANIZATION> has said it will not join the new
government because negotiations and a peace treaty with the rebel
<ORGANIZATION>Sudan People's Liberation Army</ORGANIZATION> would mean a suspension of the
<ORGANIZATION>Islamic Sharia</ORGANIZATION> law.
   <LOCATION>Malaysia</LOCATION>'s deputy home affairs minister, <PERSON>Megat Junid Megat Ayub</PERSON>,
told reporters the <ORGANIZATION>Newsweek</ORGANIZATION> and Far Eastern Economic Review issues
were banned because the contents would have a deterimental effect on
Moslems, whose faith is the official religion.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Malaysian Home Affairs Ministry</ORGANIZATION> must receive a copy of all
incoming foreign publications including newspapers. Sometimes
articles or parts of articles are blackened out and occasionally the
entire issue is banned.
</TEXT>
